		<div id="comment_body_64753662"><p>Perhaps it was fake at his crappy-ass fraudulent consulting company, but it was a real problem.  I fixed at least 6 different products that would have blown up, but did not because I fixed them. This included products that kept shipping of critical (and non-critical) goods going. You would have had a lot of dead in the water (or at least not coordinated) big rigs as their shipping fleet location, communication, and tracking systems broke.</p><p>And that was the thing about Y2K - we figured out there was a problem, we all agreed there was a problem, and we put in the money and effort (a lot of 1999) to fix the problem before it exploded.  And we mostly succeeded.  Which, I know, is completely incomprehensible now - you'd have a legion of Y2K deniers declaring it could never happen, it'd get completely politicized with certain political parties passing laws forbidding anyone from 'wasting taxpayer money' working on fixing the 'fake Y2K problem' before it turned into a complete clusterf@#$. And of course there's no longer any money or will to fix anything before it completely craters and costs 100x to fix it.</p><p>I was there. It was real.  We fixed it before it happened. It was a different time.</p></div>
	</div>

